This equation shows that the updated detection set \(\mathcal{D}_v^{(k+1)}\) is obtained by applying a fusion operation \(\oplus\) between the existing detections \(\mathcal{D}_v^{(k)}\) and the new retained detections \(\mathcal{D}_{\text{retained},v}^{(k)}\).

Below Equation (15), the fusion operation \(\oplus\) is defined in Equation (16) as:

\[
\mathcal{D} \oplus \mathcal{D}' = \bigcup_{d' \in \mathcal{D}'} (\mathcal{D} \oplus d')
\]

And further, the per-detection fusion is defined in Equation (17) as a conditional operation:

\[
\mathcal{D} \oplus d_{\text{new}} =
\begin{cases}
\mathcal{D} \cup \{d_{\text{new}}\} & \text{if } \forall d_{\text{exist}} \in \mathcal{D}, \neg \phi(d_{\text{new}}, d_{\text{exist}}) \\
\mathcal{D} \setminus d_{\text{exist}} \cup \mathcal{F}(d_{\text{new}}, d_{\text{exist}}) & \text{if } \exists d_{\text{exist}} \in \mathcal{D}, \phi(d_{\text{new}}, d_{\text{exist}})
\end{cases}
\]

This indicates that if there is no overlap (i.e., \(\neg \phi(d_{\text{new}}, d_{\text{exist}})\)), the new detection is simply added. If there is overlap, the existing detection is removed and replaced with a fused detection using \(\mathcal{F}\). This implies that the new retained detections are filtered based on their overlap with existing detections before being added.

