From the retrieved page (Page 3), I can see Equation (5) explicitly defining the False Non-Match Rate (FNMR):

$$
\text{FNMR}(\sigma) = \frac{|\{I_S \in \mathcal{I}_{\text{low-quality}} \mid Q(I_S) \geq \sigma\}|}{|\{I_S \mid Q(I_S) \geq \sigma\}|}
$$

This equation measures the proportion of low-quality scans that are incorrectly accepted (i.e., their quality score $Q(I_S)$ is ≥ σ, so they pass the gatekeeper). Therefore, FNMR measures the rate at which low-quality samples are incorrectly accepted.

Next, I need to determine how FNMR changes as the quality threshold σ increases. As σ increases, the gatekeeper becomes stricter — only higher-quality samples will have $Q(I_S) \geq \sigma$. This means fewer low-quality samples will pass the threshold, reducing the numerator of the FNMR fraction. The denominator also decreases, but since we are rejecting more low-quality samples, the overall FNMR should decrease.

Thus, FNMR decreases as σ increases.

This matches option C: "FNMR measures the rate at which low-quality samples are incorrectly accepted; it decreases as σ increases."

<answer>C. FNMR measures the rate at which low-quality samples are incorrectly accepted; it decreases as σ increases.</answer>
