From the retrieved page (Page 29), I can see Equation (15), which defines the mean pairwise overlap as:

$$
M_{\text{iou\_overlap}} = \frac{1}{N_{\text{pairs}}} \sum_{p<q} \text{IoU}(B_p, B_q)
$$

where $ N_{\text{pairs}} = \binom{N_{\text{bboxes}}}{2} $, meaning the number of unordered pairs of bounding boxes grows quadratically with the number of bounding boxes.

This implies that as the number of bounding boxes increases, the denominator (number of pairs) increases quadratically. However, the numerator is the sum of IoU values over all pairs. If the IoU values themselves do not increase proportionally (which they typically don’t unless there’s a systematic increase in overlap), then the average will be diluted by the increasing number of pairs.

Therefore, unless the IoU values of new pairs are significantly higher than existing ones, the mean pairwise overlap tends to decrease as the number of boxes increases due to the quadratic growth in the number of pairs.

This supports option A: “It decreases because the number of pairs grows quadratically, diluting the average overlap.”

