This equation defines the rotation error $\Delta \hat{\mathbf{R}}$ as the arccosine of a term involving the trace of the product of the estimated rotation matrix $\hat{\mathbf{R}}^\top$ and the ground-truth rotation matrix $\mathbf{R}$, adjusted by subtracting 1 and dividing by 2.

The expression $\text{trace}(\hat{\mathbf{R}}^\top \mathbf{R})$ is known in rotation theory to be related to the cosine of the angle between two rotation matrices. Specifically, for two 3x3 rotation matrices, the trace of their product is equal to $1 + 2\cos\theta$, where $\theta$ is the angle between them. Therefore, $\frac{\text{trace}(\hat{\mathbf{R}}^\top \mathbf{R}) - 1}{2} = \cos\theta$, and taking the arccos gives us the angle $\theta$, which is the rotation error.

