From the retrieved page (Page 3), I can see Equation (2) and the definition of the indicator function $ H_i(u) $. The function is defined as:

$$
H_i(u) = 
\begin{cases} 
0, & \text{if } \phi_i = M'(u) \\
1, & \text{if } \phi_i \neq M'(u) 
\end{cases}
$$

This means that $ H_i(u) $ is 0 when the Gaussian’s assigned class $ \phi_i $ matches the ground truth class $ M'(u) $ of pixel $ u $, and 1 otherwise. The boundary loss $ \mathcal{L}_{bound}(u) $ uses this function to penalize Gaussians that contribute to pixels of different classes.

The accompanying text states: “To ensure that each Gaussian subsequently contributes only to pixels of its class, we introduce a boundary loss that penalizes Gaussians contributing to pixels of different classes.” It further explains: “When a Gaussian renders to a pixel of a different class, the loss rewards reducing its opacity, changing its shape and/or shifting it away from the boundary.”

This indicates that the design intent of $ H_i(u) $ is to penalize Gaussians for contributing to pixels of different classes, thereby encouraging them to adjust their position, shape, or opacity to avoid boundaries.

This aligns with option **B**.

